1
00:00:39,033 --> 00:00:40,300
<i> You killed my daughter!</i>

2
00:00:40,433 --> 00:00:41,700
<i> I didn't kill her!</i>

3
00:00:41,833 --> 00:00:44,667
<i>Miss Hazel, what can you say now
that the other suspect,</i>

4
00:00:44,800 --> 00:00:46,167
<i>Coleen Cruz, has been arrested?</i>

5
00:00:46,300 --> 00:00:48,200
<i>It's useless talking
to that girl.</i>

6
00:00:48,333 --> 00:00:50,733
<i>She doesn't know
how to admit what she did.</i>

7
00:00:50,867 --> 00:00:52,633
<i>It's like you're
killing my daughter.</i>

8
00:00:52,767 --> 00:00:54,900
<i>She deserves the death penalty.</i>

9
00:00:55,033 --> 00:00:56,167
<i> You're a demon.</i>

10
00:00:57,767 --> 00:00:58,733
<i> Viral already?</i>

11
00:00:58,867 --> 00:01:01,433
<i>Detective XY really has
a huge following.</i>

12
00:01:01,567 --> 00:01:03,367
<i>She said I'll be moved
to the city jail?</i>

13
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:05,233
<i>Sweetheart, that's not going
to happen.</i>

14
00:01:05,367 --> 00:01:07,300
<i>We'll do everything
to defend you.</i>

15
00:01:07,467 --> 00:01:10,400
<i>We just have to trust in God
and in the law.</i>

16
00:01:17,600 --> 00:01:18,667
Felma?

17
00:01:24,333 --> 00:01:28,400
I'm trying to stay strong
for Coleen.

18
00:01:28,533 --> 00:01:34,467
I'm trying to be brave
because we're all she has left.

19
00:01:36,433 --> 00:01:39,300
Felma, that's what
I'm trying to do, too.

20
00:01:39,433 --> 00:01:42,533
But it's hard if she sees us
breaking down.

21
00:01:42,700 --> 00:01:44,500
She might lose hope even more.

22
00:01:46,433 --> 00:01:49,367
But it's so hard
to stay brave.

23
00:01:51,467 --> 00:01:53,067
I feel weak, too.

24
00:01:54,900 --> 00:01:59,667
I'm scared of what
Hazel's threats might do

25
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:00,733
to our daughter.

26
00:02:01,800 --> 00:02:08,600
I'm scared because everything
isn't under our control.

27
00:02:08,733 --> 00:02:11,900
Look at the bail hearing.

28
00:02:14,633 --> 00:02:16,267
We couldn't do a thing.

29
00:02:17,500 --> 00:02:19,500
Felma, we can still fix that.

30
00:02:19,633 --> 00:02:23,100
It's just that the government
offices are closed.

31
00:02:23,233 --> 00:02:25,300
That's why we couldn't
file her bail.

32
00:02:25,433 --> 00:02:27,533
Exactly!

33
00:02:27,667 --> 00:02:31,367
Such a simple thing,
and we still can't control it.

34
00:02:31,500 --> 00:02:34,700
What more when we go to court?

35
00:02:37,633 --> 00:02:40,900
Remember what I told you before?

36
00:02:41,033 --> 00:02:42,767
One day at a time.

37
00:02:44,933 --> 00:02:47,033
Let's not carry the weight
of tomorrow

38
00:02:47,200 --> 00:02:48,133
before it even happens.

39
00:03:16,900 --> 00:03:19,433
Boss, you need to see this.

40
00:03:21,667 --> 00:03:24,033
<i>I don't know what game
you're playing, Hazel.</i>

41
00:03:24,167 --> 00:03:26,567
<i>You really called
these reporters here?</i>

42
00:03:26,700 --> 00:03:28,433
<i> For what?</i>

43
00:03:28,567 --> 00:03:30,667
<i>To make a spectacle
out of my daughter?</i>

44
00:03:30,800 --> 00:03:32,267
<i> Don't be paranoid.</i>

45
00:03:32,400 --> 00:03:34,767
<i> They're here to do their jobs.</i>

46
00:03:34,900 --> 00:03:36,967
<i> Their job is to report.</i>

47
00:03:37,100 --> 00:03:38,633
<i> Or are you just ashamed</i>

48
00:03:38,767 --> 00:03:43,400
<i>that the whole world might learn
your daughter killed mine?</i>

49
00:03:45,667 --> 00:03:47,367
When did this happen, and where?

50
00:03:47,500 --> 00:03:48,267
Just a while ago.

51
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:49,267
At the precinct

52
00:03:49,400 --> 00:03:51,200
where Miss Felma's daughter
is detained.

53
00:03:51,333 --> 00:03:53,167
Arjun, cancel my flight.

54
00:03:54,567 --> 00:03:56,633
And call Attorney Vital.

55
00:03:56,767 --> 00:03:58,767
Please tell him
to meet me ASAP.

56
00:03:58,900 --> 00:03:59,833
Okay, Boss.

57
00:04:18,867 --> 00:04:21,067
Good that you came.

58
00:04:21,200 --> 00:04:23,533
I wanted to talk to you.

59
00:04:23,667 --> 00:04:25,667
What are you doing here?

60
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:27,900
Didn't I tell you to stop
visiting Jessica?

61
00:04:29,400 --> 00:04:30,767
Jessica is my daughter.

62
00:04:30,900 --> 00:04:33,300
I have every right to mourn her,
any time I want.

63
00:04:34,533 --> 00:04:35,700
You?

64
00:04:35,833 --> 00:04:39,300
You're the one who has no right
barging in and hurting Coleen!

65
00:04:39,433 --> 00:04:41,900
Your illegitimate family
has really blinded you.

66
00:04:43,633 --> 00:04:47,667
Coleen killed Jessica,
and you're still defending her?

67
00:04:47,800 --> 00:04:49,267
I'm not taking sides.

68
00:04:51,100 --> 00:04:54,467
All I'm asking for
is a little consideration.

69
00:04:55,267 --> 00:04:56,867
Fine, you're angry.

70
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:58,933
You want revenge.

71
00:04:59,067 --> 00:05:02,000
But to smear her name in public?

72
00:05:02,167 --> 00:05:03,100
To break her spirit?

73
00:05:03,233 --> 00:05:05,367
To destroy my family?

74
00:05:05,500 --> 00:05:09,100
Hazel, you punish people worse
than the court ever could.

75
00:05:10,233 --> 00:05:12,300
Your family?

76
00:05:12,433 --> 00:05:15,600
Manuel, I'm just
getting started.

77
00:05:16,500 --> 00:05:17,667
Friend, that's enough.

78
00:05:17,800 --> 00:05:19,000
Hazel.

79
00:05:19,133 --> 00:05:21,367
Hazel, you're a mother too.

80
00:05:21,500 --> 00:05:22,733
What if this happened
to Jessica?

81
00:05:25,067 --> 00:05:27,167
What if she were the one
being dragged and bashed online?

82
00:05:29,067 --> 00:05:30,967
That won't happen anymore.

83
00:05:31,100 --> 00:05:32,800
Jessica's gone.

84
00:05:32,933 --> 00:05:34,533
She's dead.

85
00:05:34,700 --> 00:05:37,700
You know, maybe that's why God
took her so soon.

86
00:05:39,700 --> 00:05:42,833
To take her away from you
because you kept hurting her!

87
00:05:42,967 --> 00:05:44,100
You heartless monster!

88
00:05:44,233 --> 00:05:45,567
Friend! Friend!

89
00:05:45,700 --> 00:05:46,333
You, of all people...

90
00:05:46,467 --> 00:05:47,900
Hazel!

91
00:05:48,033 --> 00:05:49,867
You have no respect
for our daughter!

92
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:51,333
- No respect at all!
- Stop it!

93
00:05:51,467 --> 00:05:52,233
- You're always like this!
- Friend!

94
00:05:52,367 --> 00:05:53,800
Always taking
your family's side!

95
00:05:53,933 --> 00:05:55,100
Why do you keep hurting my dad?

96
00:05:55,233 --> 00:05:56,400
Let go of me!

97
00:06:05,133 --> 00:06:07,533
I don't fight women, okay?

98
00:06:07,700 --> 00:06:08,733
Especially women older than me.

99
00:06:10,300 --> 00:06:11,400
But what you're doing,
hurting people like this,

100
00:06:11,533 --> 00:06:13,167
is wrong.

101
00:06:13,300 --> 00:06:15,800
I let it slide when you went
after my mom and my sister.

102
00:06:17,067 --> 00:06:19,733
But if you ever dare lay a hand
on my dad in front of me again,

103
00:06:19,867 --> 00:06:22,067
I swear, I'll fight back.

104
00:06:22,200 --> 00:06:22,867
- What?
- Jeff.

105
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:24,100
Why?

106
00:06:24,233 --> 00:06:25,533
- Are you threatening me?
- Yes, I'm threatening you!

107
00:06:27,100 --> 00:06:28,767
If you don't stop
harassing my family, my dad,

108
00:06:28,900 --> 00:06:29,700
and especially Coleen...

109
00:06:31,900 --> 00:06:33,133
you'll be dealing with me.

110
00:06:41,467 --> 00:06:43,467
Dad, let's go.

111
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:45,067
We're just wasting
our time here.

112
00:06:55,567 --> 00:06:56,933
You heard that, right?

113
00:06:57,067 --> 00:06:58,167
That Jeffrey just threatened me.

114
00:06:58,300 --> 00:06:59,767
Acting like he's someone
important?

115
00:06:59,900 --> 00:07:01,600
Call Atty. Salazar.

116
00:07:01,733 --> 00:07:02,367
Hurry!

117
00:07:02,500 --> 00:07:04,933
Ask him what case we can file.

118
00:07:05,067 --> 00:07:06,967
I got a death threat!

119
00:07:07,100 --> 00:07:08,533
A death threat?

120
00:07:08,667 --> 00:07:10,300
You were the one who started
attacking earlier.

121
00:07:17,267 --> 00:07:18,300
You know, Ma'am?

122
00:07:18,433 --> 00:07:21,467
I'm sure Coleen will love this.

123
00:07:21,600 --> 00:07:25,100
You cooked all her favorites.

124
00:07:25,233 --> 00:07:27,933
I hope this brings her at least
a little comfort.

125
00:07:28,067 --> 00:07:29,933
Of course, Ma'am.

126
00:07:30,067 --> 00:07:32,300
- There's a lot.
- Everything's ready.

127
00:07:32,433 --> 00:07:34,333
- Here, this too.
- Oh, Manuel.

128
00:07:34,467 --> 00:07:35,767
Where did you two go?

129
00:07:35,900 --> 00:07:39,767
Weren't we supposed to bring
lunch to Coleen?

130
00:07:39,900 --> 00:07:42,433
We just stopped by
Jessica's grave for a bit.

131
00:07:44,967 --> 00:07:45,833
How was it?

132
00:07:45,967 --> 00:07:47,133
Was Hazel there?

133
00:07:47,300 --> 00:07:48,533
Did you run into her again?

134
00:07:54,800 --> 00:07:55,567
No, Mom.

135
00:07:57,033 --> 00:07:59,800
Anyway, we'll just
take a quick shower.

136
00:07:59,933 --> 00:08:00,933
It's so sticky outside.

137
00:08:01,067 --> 00:08:01,800
It's so hot.

138
00:08:03,267 --> 00:08:04,633
Aren't you going to eat
breakfast first?

139
00:08:05,667 --> 00:08:07,633
Maybe after we shower.

140
00:08:07,767 --> 00:08:09,867
Sir, it's better to eat
while it's still hot.

141
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:11,700
Fine, but hurry, okay?

142
00:08:11,833 --> 00:08:12,300
Yes, Mom.

143
00:08:12,433 --> 00:08:13,433
We're leaving soon.

144
00:08:13,567 --> 00:08:15,433
- Okay, Mom.
- And the food will get cold.

145
00:08:15,567 --> 00:08:17,567
What about the coffee, Ma'am?

146
00:08:17,700 --> 00:08:19,367
We prepared so much.

147
00:08:22,633 --> 00:08:25,600
Cruz, someone wants
to speak with you.

148
00:08:25,733 --> 00:08:27,267
Is it my mom and dad?

149
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:28,000
No.

150
00:08:29,500 --> 00:08:32,033
If it's Hazel, then no thanks.

151
00:08:33,967 --> 00:08:35,133
Coleen?

152
00:08:35,267 --> 00:08:36,533
If I may call you Coleen?

153
00:08:36,667 --> 00:08:39,600
I'm Jiro Gomez,
reporter from PNTV42.

154
00:08:39,733 --> 00:08:41,567
Can I interview you?

155
00:08:41,700 --> 00:08:42,500
No.

156
00:08:42,633 --> 00:08:44,700
You can tell
your side of the story.

157
00:08:44,833 --> 00:08:46,467
I said no!

158
00:08:46,600 --> 00:08:49,500
My lawyer told me
not to speak to anyone.

159
00:08:49,633 --> 00:08:52,333
But this is your chance
to clear your name.

160
00:08:52,467 --> 00:08:54,033
I said no!

161
00:08:54,200 --> 00:08:55,733
Can you leave Coleen alone?

162
00:08:59,200 --> 00:09:01,367
You're stripping her
of her dignity

163
00:09:01,500 --> 00:09:03,167
and even her right to privacy!

164
00:09:06,167 --> 00:09:07,033
Uncle Noah?

165
00:09:08,733 --> 00:09:09,567
Coleen, sweetheart...

166
00:09:14,833 --> 00:09:15,600
How are you?

167
00:09:19,867 --> 00:09:20,633
I'm here now, dear.

168
00:09:25,767 --> 00:09:26,700
I'm here.

169
00:09:30,533 --> 00:09:32,500
That Jeffrey!

170
00:09:32,633 --> 00:09:35,100
Does Jeffrey think
he can scare me?

171
00:09:35,233 --> 00:09:38,633
Fine. I'll ruin his sister
even more.

172
00:09:38,767 --> 00:09:41,567
Attorney, what else can we do?

173
00:09:41,700 --> 00:09:47,000
Mrs. Cruz, we're here to work on
what we have to help our case.

174
00:09:47,133 --> 00:09:50,267
Not to smear the defendant.

175
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:54,167
Attorney, what if we look for
one of Coleen's old classmates?

176
00:09:54,300 --> 00:09:58,467
Maybe she had enemies,

177
00:09:58,600 --> 00:10:00,200
someone she had fought
with before.

178
00:10:00,333 --> 00:10:01,733
Right? Then we can stir it up.

179
00:10:01,900 --> 00:10:04,433
If we have to bribe someone,
pay them,

180
00:10:04,567 --> 00:10:06,167
just to destroy Coleen's
reputation even more.

181
00:10:06,300 --> 00:10:07,633
Like what you did
to that driver?

182
00:10:09,300 --> 00:10:11,833
Attorney, are you really
not over that?

183
00:10:11,967 --> 00:10:14,400
I talked to Timo Malabanan.

184
00:10:14,533 --> 00:10:16,933
I told him and explained
carefully

185
00:10:17,233 --> 00:10:20,500
that perjury is a serious crime.

186
00:10:20,633 --> 00:10:22,933
That he could still change
his testimony.

187
00:10:24,800 --> 00:10:25,667
And?

188
00:10:29,733 --> 00:10:31,067
He stood firm.

189
00:10:31,200 --> 00:10:33,133
He said what he saw was true,

190
00:10:33,267 --> 00:10:35,300
that Coleen really pushed
Jessica.

191
00:10:37,567 --> 00:10:39,400
See?

192
00:10:39,533 --> 00:10:41,200
There you go!

193
00:10:41,333 --> 00:10:42,900
I just don't understand

194
00:10:43,033 --> 00:10:46,500
why you're wasting your time
doubting, Attorney.

195
00:10:46,633 --> 00:10:49,800
Instead of figuring out
how to speed this case up.

196
00:10:51,033 --> 00:10:54,567
So that girl can
finally be sentenced.

197
00:10:54,700 --> 00:10:57,800
Mrs. Cruz, these things
take time.

198
00:10:58,900 --> 00:11:00,700
The arraignment's in a few days.

199
00:11:00,833 --> 00:11:02,200
Why do you seem like
you're in such a rush?

200
00:11:03,733 --> 00:11:06,200
So Jeffrey can't
threaten me anymore.

201
00:11:06,333 --> 00:11:07,900
And so that illegitimate family
can stop

202
00:11:08,067 --> 00:11:09,700
acting like they're superior.

203
00:11:27,633 --> 00:11:30,667
I still can't believe
you're here, Uncle Noah.

204
00:11:32,333 --> 00:11:33,200
I'm in town, dear.

205
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:36,400
When I heard what happened
to you,

206
00:11:39,233 --> 00:11:41,967
I couldn't stop myself
from checking on you.

207
00:11:44,600 --> 00:11:46,833
I'm not okay here, Uncle.

208
00:11:48,233 --> 00:11:49,633
Everything feels strange.

209
00:11:51,333 --> 00:11:53,433
It's my first time being away
from my family.

210
00:11:55,100 --> 00:11:57,633
Uncle, I didn't do
anything wrong.

211
00:11:57,767 --> 00:12:01,433
Hazel's accusing me,
but it's not true.

212
00:12:01,567 --> 00:12:03,933
I could never do that
to my sister.

213
00:12:04,067 --> 00:12:05,300
I know, sweetheart. I know.

214
00:12:07,667 --> 00:12:09,267
I may not know every details...

215
00:12:11,933 --> 00:12:13,933
but I believe you're innocent.

216
00:12:14,933 --> 00:12:15,600
I believe you.

217
00:12:17,267 --> 00:12:19,600
Thank you, Uncle.

218
00:12:19,733 --> 00:12:23,233
When someone encourages me
like that,

219
00:12:23,367 --> 00:12:25,933
it gives me a little strength,
even just a bit.

220
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:33,367
I'm just glad to see you again.

221
00:12:35,200 --> 00:12:37,433
And I'm grateful you're here.

222
00:12:45,400 --> 00:12:46,633
Stay strong, my dear.

223
00:12:49,633 --> 00:12:50,567
I'm here, okay?

224
00:12:54,667 --> 00:12:56,167
Sir, wait.

225
00:12:56,300 --> 00:12:58,567
Maybe just five more minutes?

226
00:12:58,700 --> 00:13:01,567
This is the first time I've
talked to my Uncle Noah again.

227
00:13:01,700 --> 00:13:02,567
I just escorted them here.

228
00:13:05,467 --> 00:13:06,067
Thank you.

229
00:13:16,800 --> 00:13:19,800
Coleen, this is Arjun,
my executive assistant.

230
00:13:21,533 --> 00:13:25,500
And this is Atty. Artemio Vital,
my lawyer.

231
00:13:25,633 --> 00:13:27,867
This Coleen is the one that
we are going to help, Attorney.

232
00:13:29,333 --> 00:13:31,667
Attorney, any news?

233
00:13:31,800 --> 00:13:36,100
I coordinated with Atty. Yeban
about filing for bail.

234
00:13:36,233 --> 00:13:38,000
Good thing you know
the executive judge.

235
00:13:38,133 --> 00:13:38,933
That's why he's able
to fast-track it

236
00:13:39,067 --> 00:13:40,833
to the presiding judge.

237
00:13:40,967 --> 00:13:43,167
We convinced them that
this is a special case,

238
00:13:43,300 --> 00:13:46,233
so they're processing
the paperwork as we speak.

239
00:13:51,100 --> 00:13:51,967
Did you hear that, sweetie?

240
00:13:53,300 --> 00:13:56,367
You're getting out.

241
00:13:56,533 --> 00:13:58,500
Am I getting out?

242
00:13:58,633 --> 00:13:59,533
Today?

243
00:14:01,100 --> 00:14:01,767
Yes.

244
00:14:03,600 --> 00:14:05,267
Within the day.

245
00:14:05,400 --> 00:14:06,567
Thank you, Attorney!

246
00:14:08,100 --> 00:14:10,300
You should be thanking Noah.

247
00:14:10,433 --> 00:14:13,533
He acted so quickly
to speed up your release.

248
00:14:15,033 --> 00:14:17,067
Thank you, Uncle.

249
00:14:17,200 --> 00:14:18,067
Thank you.

250
00:14:25,167 --> 00:14:27,867
Atty. Yeban still can't be
reached.

251
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:31,233
Mom, maybe he's just busy
arranging Coleen's bail.

252
00:14:31,400 --> 00:14:32,567
Message him instead.

253
00:14:32,700 --> 00:14:33,833
Tell him we're on the way
to the precinct,

254
00:14:33,967 --> 00:14:34,967
and we'll just meet him there.

255
00:14:35,100 --> 00:14:36,100
All right.

256
00:14:36,233 --> 00:14:37,067
Yes, let's go.

257
00:14:37,200 --> 00:14:38,500
We might be late.

258
00:14:38,633 --> 00:14:39,833
<i> Coleen might think...</i>

259
00:14:39,967 --> 00:14:41,633
<i> Okay, let's go.</i>

260
00:14:41,767 --> 00:14:42,967
Coleen! Coleen!

261
00:14:43,100 --> 00:14:43,567
Didang!

262
00:14:43,700 --> 00:14:45,333
How are you?

263
00:14:45,467 --> 00:14:47,600
Coleen, I missed you!

264
00:14:47,733 --> 00:14:48,567
Come here, come here!

265
00:14:48,700 --> 00:14:50,867
Ma'am! Ma'am!
Your youngest is here!

266
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:52,000
Coleen!

267
00:14:52,133 --> 00:14:54,000
Coleen's here!

268
00:14:54,133 --> 00:14:54,833
Coleen?

269
00:14:54,967 --> 00:14:56,000
Coleen?

270
00:14:56,133 --> 00:14:58,500
- Andrea!
- Baby!

271
00:14:58,633 --> 00:14:59,867
- Coleen...
- How did you...

272
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:00,500
How did you get out?

273
00:15:00,633 --> 00:15:01,667
How did you come home?

274
00:15:01,833 --> 00:15:02,467
Dad!

275
00:15:02,600 --> 00:15:03,533
- Sweetheart!
- What happened?

276
00:15:35,367 --> 00:15:36,033
Really?

277
00:15:37,433 --> 00:15:38,000
Yes.

278
00:15:39,233 --> 00:15:40,367
Okay, okay.

279
00:15:40,500 --> 00:15:42,200
Thanks for letting me know.

280
00:15:43,467 --> 00:15:44,167
Attorney, who was that?

281
00:15:46,600 --> 00:15:49,700
Someone I know from the
Clerk of Court's office.

282
00:15:52,533 --> 00:15:54,333
They said Coleen has
already posted bail.

283
00:15:54,467 --> 00:15:55,733
What?

284
00:15:55,867 --> 00:15:57,733
How did that happen?

285
00:15:57,867 --> 00:15:59,867
I thought bail couldn't be
processed

286
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:02,333
because it's the weekend
and offices are closed?

287
00:16:02,467 --> 00:16:05,967
Mrs. Cruz, there are exceptions.

288
00:16:06,100 --> 00:16:09,867
And it still depends
on the executive judge.

289
00:16:11,267 --> 00:16:15,067
Or maybe they personally
know him.

290
00:16:15,200 --> 00:16:16,900
They know him?

291
00:16:17,033 --> 00:16:19,033
Who?

292
00:16:19,167 --> 00:16:21,933
A certain Atty. Artemio Vital,

293
00:16:22,067 --> 00:16:23,600
who's representing
Noah Salvador.

294
00:16:25,133 --> 00:16:26,967
Noah Salvador?

295
00:16:27,100 --> 00:16:28,100
<i>- Mom!
- Felma, that's enough!</i>

296
00:16:30,200 --> 00:16:30,867
<i> Who are you?</i>

297
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:31,800
<i> Why are you hurting my mother?</i>

298
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:36,633
Noah Salvador.

299
00:16:36,767 --> 00:16:40,600
The man who is hopelessly
obsessed with Flirty Felma.

300
00:16:40,733 --> 00:16:42,600
What stunt are you
pulling this time?

301
00:16:46,733 --> 00:16:49,200
Good thing Uncle Noah arrived.

302
00:16:49,333 --> 00:16:51,400
Because of him, the reporter
finally left me alone.

303
00:16:51,533 --> 00:16:53,567
He stopped bothering me.

304
00:16:53,700 --> 00:16:56,900
And the best part is,
he helped me get out.

305
00:16:59,100 --> 00:17:01,200
I actually spoke to Atty. Yeban.

306
00:17:01,333 --> 00:17:05,767
He was about to process the bail
as soon as their office resumed.

307
00:17:05,900 --> 00:17:08,500
Then your lawyer called him.

308
00:17:08,633 --> 00:17:10,700
And told him everything
was already taken care of.

309
00:17:10,833 --> 00:17:15,033
We have a contact in the
executive judge's office.

310
00:17:15,200 --> 00:17:17,067
Attorney Vital and I
requested a little help.

311
00:17:18,900 --> 00:17:20,267
Thank you, Noah.

312
00:17:20,400 --> 00:17:22,100
Thank you so much.

313
00:17:22,233 --> 00:17:23,233
Think nothing of it, Felma.

314
00:17:25,300 --> 00:17:27,300
Thank you, Uncle Noah.

315
00:17:27,433 --> 00:17:30,833
You don't know how much mom
couldn't sleep from worrying.

316
00:17:31,567 --> 00:17:33,100
Honestly, all of us.

317
00:17:33,233 --> 00:17:34,800
We were all so worried
about Coleen.

318
00:17:34,933 --> 00:17:37,067
Uncle, thank God you're here
in Manila.

319
00:17:37,200 --> 00:17:38,767
Perfect timing.

320
00:17:38,900 --> 00:17:42,467
Actually, I was attending
a business conference.

321
00:17:42,600 --> 00:17:44,800
I was about to board the plane.

322
00:17:44,933 --> 00:17:47,800
Then, when I heard what
happened to Coleen,

323
00:17:47,933 --> 00:17:49,900
I thought maybe I could help.

324
00:17:50,067 --> 00:17:51,467
You really did help.

325
00:17:51,600 --> 00:17:53,933
Oh, yes.

326
00:17:54,067 --> 00:17:55,167
<i> Amazing, right?</i>

327
00:18:04,467 --> 00:18:05,967
Dad, are you okay?

328
00:18:07,733 --> 00:18:08,300
Yeah.

329
00:18:12,367 --> 00:18:14,000
What's wrong?

330
00:18:14,133 --> 00:18:15,000
Nothing.

331
00:18:15,133 --> 00:18:15,867
Go on, keep eating.

332
00:18:18,633 --> 00:18:22,033
Noah, thank you so much
for helping Coleen.

333
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:25,067
I'll be grateful for that
for the rest of my life.

334
00:18:26,633 --> 00:18:27,667
It's nothing, Manuel.

335
00:18:27,800 --> 00:18:29,400
I'm just glad I could help
my daughter...

336
00:18:33,267 --> 00:18:36,633
I mean the people
I consider family.

337
00:18:45,500 --> 00:18:49,833
Uncle Noah, do you want
to try Didang's Sinigang?

338
00:18:49,967 --> 00:18:51,033
It's her specialty.

339
00:18:52,200 --> 00:18:53,067
Sure, it looks delicious.

340
00:18:53,200 --> 00:18:54,467
- Yes.
- Go ahead.

341
00:18:58,067 --> 00:18:59,100
<i> Thank you.</i>

342
00:19:13,767 --> 00:19:15,100
Coffee, Uncle.

343
00:19:15,233 --> 00:19:15,900
Thank you.

344
00:19:24,033 --> 00:19:26,033
I wanted to apologize
to both of you.

345
00:19:28,700 --> 00:19:31,767
Things didn't end well
between us back then.

346
00:19:31,900 --> 00:19:34,133
<i>Are we still allowed
to come to you?</i>

347
00:19:34,267 --> 00:19:36,500
<i> Your mother cast me aside.</i>

348
00:19:36,633 --> 00:19:38,333
<i> Wouldn't it be too much</i>

349
00:19:38,467 --> 00:19:41,433
<i>if I kept forcing myself back
into your family, dear?</i>

350
00:19:44,800 --> 00:19:46,167
I was cold and abrasive.

351
00:19:49,100 --> 00:19:49,933
I hurt you.

352
00:19:51,533 --> 00:19:54,067
That was a long time ago,
Uncle Noah.

353
00:19:54,200 --> 00:19:56,267
A lot has happened since then.

354
00:19:56,400 --> 00:20:00,033
I made peace with mom and dad,
too.

355
00:20:01,100 --> 00:20:01,967
It's all okay now.

356
00:20:03,200 --> 00:20:06,167
And in a way, leaving turned out
to be a blessing.

357
00:20:07,700 --> 00:20:09,867
We learned to stand
on our own feet.

358
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:12,467
And whatever problems came,
we found ways to solve them.

359
00:20:14,867 --> 00:20:15,600
You know...

360
00:20:17,467 --> 00:20:19,900
even when I was in Davao,

361
00:20:20,033 --> 00:20:22,033
even when we weren't talking...

362
00:20:23,367 --> 00:20:25,000
I still heard things about you.

363
00:20:26,700 --> 00:20:27,933
I still thought about you.

364
00:20:29,733 --> 00:20:32,800
You can't erase what we went
through together that easily.

365
00:20:34,067 --> 00:20:35,467
Because I treated you
like my own children.

366
00:20:50,800 --> 00:20:52,767
I don't even know what to say.

367
00:20:53,833 --> 00:20:56,033
I feel ashamed after everything
that happened between us.

368
00:20:59,367 --> 00:21:00,533
I hurt you.

369
00:21:03,067 --> 00:21:04,500
Felma...

370
00:21:04,633 --> 00:21:04,833
Please.

371
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:07,200
Let me.

372
00:21:07,333 --> 00:21:11,367
I didn't expect
that after everything...

373
00:21:13,900 --> 00:21:14,967
you'd still be here.

374
00:21:16,233 --> 00:21:17,467
Helping me.

375
00:21:18,533 --> 00:21:20,500
Just like you helped
Jeffrey before.

376
00:21:23,233 --> 00:21:24,100
<i> Please don't be angry.</i>

377
00:21:24,233 --> 00:21:25,833
<i>Don't take me away
from my mother.</i>

378
00:21:25,967 --> 00:21:28,933
<i>Please, don't take me away
from my mom.</i>

379
00:21:29,067 --> 00:21:30,800
<i>Maybe you could
forgive the child?</i>

380
00:21:31,833 --> 00:21:35,667
It's like whenever
we're cornered,

381
00:21:35,800 --> 00:21:37,867
whenever we have no idea
what to do...

382
00:21:39,233 --> 00:21:42,567
that's when you show up
to help us.

383
00:21:43,667 --> 00:21:44,633
Maybe it's a coincidence.

384
00:21:47,367 --> 00:21:49,100
I've wanted to reach out
for a long time.

385
00:21:50,300 --> 00:21:51,067
But I was embarrassed.

386
00:21:54,233 --> 00:21:55,767
I thought maybe
I wasn't welcome anymore.

387
00:21:56,467 --> 00:21:57,933
Of course, you're very welcome.

388
00:22:03,033 --> 00:22:05,233
We're still friends, aren't we?

389
00:22:06,800 --> 00:22:07,500
Thank you.

390
00:22:08,733 --> 00:22:11,067
I'm extremely grateful.

391
00:22:12,633 --> 00:22:17,633
Felma, you were once a very
important part of my life.

392
00:22:19,767 --> 00:22:22,167
I was here while the kids
were growing up.

393
00:22:23,233 --> 00:22:24,233
They were like my own.

394
00:22:25,633 --> 00:22:26,833
I just did what I could...

395
00:22:28,700 --> 00:22:29,600
as a father.

396
00:22:34,033 --> 00:22:35,433
Again, thank you.

397
00:23:18,400 --> 00:23:21,400
Sir Manuel, we're close now,
right?

398
00:23:22,167 --> 00:23:23,533
Can I ask you something?

399
00:23:24,800 --> 00:23:26,600
Are you jealous of Sir Noah?

400
00:23:29,733 --> 00:23:30,600
Why would I be jealous?

401
00:23:30,733 --> 00:23:32,233
He's just helping.

402
00:23:33,600 --> 00:23:34,633
Well, yeah.

403
00:23:34,767 --> 00:23:37,133
Sir Noah is genuinely kind.

404
00:23:37,267 --> 00:23:40,167
Actually, he really
loves the kids.

405
00:23:40,300 --> 00:23:44,800
And he treated them
like his own.

406
00:23:44,933 --> 00:23:47,000
<i> Especially Coleen.</i>

407
00:23:47,133 --> 00:23:49,967
He's been there
since she was a baby.

408
00:23:50,100 --> 00:23:52,567
He practically became
a father to her.

409
00:23:56,733 --> 00:23:58,467
Sir...

410
00:23:58,600 --> 00:24:00,300
I'm still Team Manuel, okay?

411
00:24:00,433 --> 00:24:03,300
<i> Don't get me wrong.</i>

412
00:24:03,433 --> 00:24:04,867
I'm just sharing what I know.

413
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:06,800
Don't feel guilty.

414
00:24:06,933 --> 00:24:07,933
No.

415
00:24:08,067 --> 00:24:10,800
In fact, I'm grateful Noah
was here when I wasn't.

416
00:24:10,933 --> 00:24:13,700
Felma needed someone beside her.

417
00:24:13,833 --> 00:24:16,467
Yes, and you know what, Sir?

418
00:24:16,600 --> 00:24:19,333
Sir Noah really, really
loves Ma'am Felma.

419
00:24:19,467 --> 00:24:23,033
I mean the kind of love
you can feel.

420
00:24:23,167 --> 00:24:25,800
A kind of love that
doesn't just disappear.

421
00:24:26,933 --> 00:24:28,600
What are you even saying?

422
00:24:28,767 --> 00:24:31,633
No, I just thought,

423
00:24:31,767 --> 00:24:35,300
didn't Ma'am Felma
reject Sir Noah before?

424
00:24:35,433 --> 00:24:38,033
And Sir Noah knows
you're here now.

425
00:24:38,167 --> 00:24:40,167
So why did he come back?

426
00:24:40,300 --> 00:24:43,067
Does he truly just want
to help Coleen?

427
00:24:43,200 --> 00:24:44,900
Or did he return because
he still has feelings

428
00:24:45,033 --> 00:24:46,400
for Ma'am Felma?

429
00:24:46,533 --> 00:24:47,400
What do you think?

430
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:54,500
Coleen hasn't even warmed
her seat in jail,

431
00:24:54,633 --> 00:24:55,567
and they already let her out.

432
00:24:55,700 --> 00:24:57,233
She'll still end up behind bars.

433
00:24:57,367 --> 00:24:59,267
But it's a good thing
Uncle Noah arrived.

434
00:24:59,400 --> 00:25:01,500
He still cares about us
even now.

435
00:25:01,633 --> 00:25:04,000
Is he just playing
the knight in shining armor?

436
00:25:04,167 --> 00:25:07,133
How does it feel when your ex
suddenly swoops in to save you?

437
00:25:07,267 --> 00:25:10,433
What I don't get is why
did he suddenly come back?

438
00:25:10,567 --> 00:25:12,367
What are you doing here?

439
00:25:12,500 --> 00:25:14,033
The same thing you're doing.

440
00:25:14,167 --> 00:25:15,700
Giving my full support
to Coleen.

441
00:25:16,833 --> 00:25:19,733
Thank you for accepting
my invitation.

442
00:25:19,867 --> 00:25:22,233
Tell me what I need to know.

443
00:25:22,367 --> 00:25:24,267
I want us to be allies.
